One

I learned to cook steak and rice, cooked too much rice, prepared too little sauce, and didn't succeed in imitating the delicious scene of food bloggers pouring rich soup over the rice. The blogger said the sauce should be a spoonful of japanese-style soy sauce, a spoonful of sake and a spoonful of "flavor. ". I had none, so I switched to light soy sauce, cooking wine, sugar and water. To tell the truth, I don't even know what "viboline" is now, if not for the blogger's thoughtful addition of "available sugar and water instead" , I might give up halfway.

Although none of the ingredients came from the original recipe, I took a bite and was pleasantly surprised to discover that the meal had more or less a "Yoshino's" flavor. I didn't want to use the word "Yoshino's" to describe the strong flavor of Bowl in Japanese style, but I couldn't think of a single, rude adjective that would instantly make sense to the reader. Speaking of which, I haven't eaten at Yoshino's in two or three years.

Two

Now it's becoming increasingly clear why people need to grow up with someone, regardless of gender, regardless of whether they're married or not. There are many inconveniences in living alone, not to mention isolation. From shopping, chopping, preparing food to cooking, as well as after the dishes, wipe the table, wipe the floor are all a package on the shoulder. The so-called efficiency is too low, about seven o'clock to go out to buy food, and then sit at the desk, will have passed nine. For a person suffering from severe essay anxiety, this is not conducive to mental health. However, in times of crisis, when the reliability of going out for "meal breaks" or ordering takeout both declines, cooking is practically the only option.

Video chatting with my parents this afternoon, they said, I can see that I have an inexplicable fear of going to the supermarket. I said yes. I think it's a very complex emotion. I don't want to get up early to go to the supermarket where the goods have just come in (I don't think I can get up either) ; I don't want to go in the daytime because I really don't want to be the only one wearing a mask on the street in broad daylight; and I'm worried about going to the supermarket, the ingredients you want are already gone; you don't want to waste a mask just by going to the supermarket. So my first choice is online shopping. Although I mentioned in yesterday's article that "my friends told me the online supermarket is due in April" , I took the chance to visit the official websites of the UK's supermarkets one by one. The results were so bizarre that I realised how terrified the British were already behind closed doors.

Ocado, the UK's largest and only online supermarket, displays a wait screen when I click on it. I'm number 7,241. If I want to go into the supermarket, I have to wait in line for more than two hours. I've never heard of it before. I never knew there was a line for online shopping. When I switched to Amazon Fresh, after I had selected the ingredients, I realized that until I left the UK in April, there was no alternative delivery time. MARKS & Spencer's online supermarket puzzled me out and did a quick tour of the store without finding any fresh vegetables. WAITROSE is the best: its website just crashed.

Three

Opening the refrigerator, I watched the logistics of running out of ammunition. My friend says we need to stay operational for another two weeks, so I'm GONNA need to load up anyway. Put on your coat, shoes, and mask, and rush in before the nearby supermarket closes.

The shelves are half-empty. I don't know if it's not to the British taste, but I was overjoyed to find a box of tomatoes, cucumbers, lettuce, chicken breasts, crab sticks, scallions, Ginger and garlic. However, the alcohol wipes are gone. A basin of cold water poured on my head, this is one of the most important necessities of my isolated life ah! Get up every morning, wash gargle after, the first thing to sit at the desk must be the computer and mobile phone with a wet towel carefully wipe again. At this point, as I write this, I have the last one left in my bag, which means I have to get new wipes tomorrow, no matter what.

Four

On the way home, I turned on my cell phone and found, ironically enough, that because I was walking so fast, my cell phone thought I was driving and canceled all my alerts. I do feel a little sweat on my back, and I think I want to get home soon. In any case, being the only person on the street with a mask on, I felt a little uncomfortable.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"From Martin Rowson / The Guardian.

Ye Zifeng describes the German attitude toward the epidemic as a paradoxical mix of anxiety and disdain. Londoners are pretty much the same. The face mask does not wear, the family door is determined to go out; at the same time, the supermarket shelf has already been emptied. If there is anxiety inside, why pretend to be dismissive on the surface? I don't understand.

Five

As a matter of fact, I would like to record in today's diary the rising anger of these two days.

Before showering last night, a friend in London's Friendagenda reposted an article by he yue, a sociologist, calling on people to "think rationally" and not "blindly criticize" . My immediate reaction was to forward to William Hanaqi, a Harvard medical professor, an article in The Guardian criticizing "Mass Immunization Policies" ; She then wanted to forward her questions about the policy to The Lancet, a professional journal. But then I thought, maybe they're just being silly, and it's useless for you to retweet them, just like it's useless if they're really stupid. When I figured it out, though, I couldn't get rid of my anger at the stupid person, so I gave up the idea of commenting on her and just blocked it out. If they do, they're likely to keep up with the debate late into the night and end up angry and unable to sleep. What's the point.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Harvard Medical Professor William Hanaqi has published an article in the Guardian Mocking "herd immunity" .

It seems to me that I should give up this habit of being too eager to "enlighten" others. It's funny, I might be an idiot myself, and I need to be enlightened. Where does enlightenment come from? Since the Opium War, says Gan, the burden of enlightenment has been on the shoulders of Chinese intellectuals. Xu Jilin said something similar. Forty years ago Huang Xiang, North Island and others hoarse in front of the Democratic Wall, also for enlightenment. But in the end? Enlightenment? I don't think so. Still, take a look at Donald Trump's tweet from last night -- did you say the West is ready for mass enlightenment? No, I didn't.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"Star Painting Exhibition" (1979) , one of the main managers, "today" painter Ma Desheng in front of the wall of democracy. Source: Today.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In 1980 by "today" , "Star" painting school, "fertile soil" and other plans of the parade, aimed at enlightenment. Source: Forty Years Today.

So Be Yourself, I said to myself. Shut up, less talking, more reading, rare isolation, more writing papers, less angry. You don't deserve to be enlightened, and you probably don't deserve to be enlightened. It's nice to be separated from each other.
